    rectoEn: '"A 300 bp spread means the market FORECASTS 5% of defaults per year" — the trap?',
    versoEn: 'WRONG on the verb: the market PRICES 5%, it does not FORECAST 5%. The implied PD is risk-neutral: it makes the spread actuarially fair while the spread contains the risk premium and the liquidity premium — so it mechanically overstates the historical frequency, often by a factor of 2 to 5. It is not that the market is wrong: it prices the stress, not the mean. The anchor: orally, a single verb separates the right answer from the trap — "to price" is not "to forecast".',
