    rectoEn: 'Spread duration: definition — and why a corporate bond is differentiated twice?',
    versoEn: 'ΔP/P ≈ −D_mod × Δs: the same arithmetic as m4\'s rate duration, but the shock comes from credit. A corporate carries TWO risks with the same duration: ΔP ≈ −D × (Δr + Δs). In calm times both sleep; in a crisis they can pull in OPPOSITE directions — spreads explode while risk-free rates fall (flight to quality): a long IG book can end a crisis almost unchanged, an HY book has no cushion. The anchor: D 7 and a crisis-style +300 bp = −21% — a BOND portfolio losing like equities, without a single realised default.',
