    versoEn: 'IG: STEEP (30 bp at 2 years, 90 at 10 years) — near-term survival is hardly in doubt, it is the far horizon that insures dearly: strategic drift, releveraging, cycle change. Distressed: often INVERTED — all the risk is concentrated on the immediate maturity (refinancing wall, covenant test); if the issuer gets through the year, the worst is behind: surviving is the information. And each rating notch shifts the whole curve upward. The anchor: an inverted spread curve is the entry sign of the distressed regime — the market switches from yield to recovery.',
